ady Isobel de Warren于1310年出生在英国肯特布拉布恩时，她的父亲Lord John de Warren36岁，母亲Agnes Wymington36岁。她于1340年与Sir Andrew Scott - Fourth Lord of Balwearie在英国肯特布拉布恩结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。她去世在英国苏格兰費伏，埋葬在英国苏格兰費伏。"},"hr":{"1310–":"1310.–preminula","1310–Female":"1310.–preminula","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1350–1406":"1350.–1406","1274–1310":"1274–1310.","1274–Female":"1274–preminula","1315":"1315","1355":"1355","1310":"1310.","1340":"1340.","1274":"1274","1350":"1350.","1382":"1382","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Balweary, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Škotska, United Kingdom","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Škotska, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"cs":{"1310–":"1310–Zesnulá","1310–Female":"1310–Zesnulá","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1274–1310":"1274–1310","1274–Female":"1274–Zesnulá","1315":"1315","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Balweary, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"1310–":"1310–Afdød","1310–Female":"1310–Afdød","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1274–1310":"1274–1310","1274–Female":"1274–Afdød","1315":"1315","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Balweary, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Skotland, United Kingdom","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotland, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"nl":{"1310–":"1310–Overleden","1310–Female":"1310–Overleden","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1274–1310":"1274–1310","1274–Female":"1274–Overleden","1315":"1315","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Balweary, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"en":{"1310–":"1310–Deceased","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1274–1310":"1274–1310","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","1315":"1315","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Balweary, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Warren","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Warin</i>, <i>Werin</i>, a borrowing of ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. Compare   Waring  .","English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from La Varrenne in Seine-Maritime, France, named with a Gaulish element probably descriptive of alluvial land or sandy soil. This was the name of a major Norman family after the Conquest. In Ireland, this name has been Gaelicized as <b>Bharain</b>.","Irish: adopted as an English form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b> (see   Murnane  ,   Warner  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Warrens","meanings":["English: variant of   Warren   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Warrener","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>warrennier</i> ‘warrener’, an officer employed to watch over game in a park or game preserve. Compare   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Murnane","meanings":["Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b>, a shortened and dissimilated form of <b>Ó Manannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Manannán</i>’, name borne in Celtic mythology by a sea god associated with the Isle of Man. All three syllables appear in the variant <b>Marrinan</b>. This name has also been Anglicized as   Warren   and   Warner  ."]},{"name":"Waren","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Warne","meanings":["shortened form of   Warren  .","occasionally a habitational name from Wearne in Somerset. The place takes its name from a lost stream-name based on British <i>verno-</i> ‘alder, swamp’.","English:"]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"Isobel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Isobel de Warren was born in 1310, in Brabourne, Kent, England, her father, Lord John de Warren, was 36 and her mother, Agnes Wymington, was 36. She married Sir Andrew Scott - Fourth Lord of Balwearie in 1340, in Brabourne, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, and was buried in Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","13